'generate_query[1].predict' predictor demos: [Example({'augmented': True, 'context': ['Thomas Keneally | Thomas Michael Keneally, AO (born 7 October 1935) is a prolific Australian novelist, playwright, and essayist. He is best known for writing "Schindler\'s Ark", the Booker Prize-winning novel of 1982 which was inspired by the efforts of Poldek Pfefferberg, a Holocaust survivor. The book would later be adapted to Steven Spielberg\'s "Schindler\'s List", which won the Academy Award for Best Picture.', 'Peter Straub | Peter Francis Straub (born March 2, 1943) is an American novelist and poet. His horror fiction has received numerous literary honors such as the Bram Stoker Award, World Fantasy Award, and International Horror Guild Award.', 'Thomas Martin Kennerly | Thomas Martin Kennerly (January 24, 1874 – July 29, 1962) was a United States federal judge. He was a Republican.'], 'question': 'Are Thomas Keneally and Peter Straub both novelists?', 'reasoning': 'To determine if Thomas Keneally and Peter Straub are both novelists, I need to focus on the key information from the provided excerpts. For Thomas Keneally, the context mentions that he is "a prolific Australian novelist, playwright, and essayist." This clearly identifies him as a novelist. For Peter Straub, the context states that he is "an American novelist and poet," which also identifies him as a novelist. Therefore, based on the information provided, both Thomas Keneally and Peter Straub are indeed novelists.', 'search_query': 'Are Thomas Keneally and Peter Straub both known for their work as novelists?'}) (input_keys=None), Example({'augmented': True, 'context': ['South Carolina National Bank of Charleston | One of the most important buildings on South Carolina’s oldest commercial street, the South Carolina National Bank building was built in 1817 as the Office of Discount and Deposit of the Second Bank of the United States. The bank was the only bank equipped to provide international banking services, which enabled the transfer of South Carolina rice and cotton to European markets. President Andrew Jackson later withdrew all government deposits, thereby destroying the bank. In 1836, when the Office of Discount and Deposit was liquidated, the Bank of Charleston purchased the building.', "Farmers' and Exchange Bank | The Farmers' and Exchange Bank is a historic commercial building at 141 East Bay Street in Charleston, South Carolina. Built in 1853–54, it is an architecturally distinctive building, with Moorish Revival features rarely seen in the United States. The building is recognizable for its use of muqarnas—characteristic of Persian and North African architecture—as well as its large arched windows and striking red sandstone facade. It was declared a National Historic Landmark in 1973.", 'First Citizens Bank of South Carolina | First Citizens Bank of South Carolina is a subsidiary of First Citizens BancShares, Inc., of Raleigh, North Carolina; it is the largest bank in the United States controlled by a single family. Prior to its acquisition by First Citizens BancShares Inc. of Raleigh, First Citizens Bancorporation, Inc. was a bank holding company based in Columbia, South Carolina with over $8 billion in assets. First Citizens Bank of South Carolina had branches in both South Carolina and Georgia. It was the second-largest commercial bank headquartered in South Carolina.'], 'question': 'What country does South Carolina National Bank of Charleston and Andrew Jackson have in common?', 'reasoning': 'To find the country that South Carolina National Bank of Charleston and Andrew Jackson have in common, I need to identify the location of the bank and the country of Andrew Jackson. The South Carolina National Bank of Charleston operates in South Carolina, a state in the United States. Andrew Jackson was the 7th President of the United States, which also indicates the country.', 'search_query': 'What country was Andrew Jackson, the 7th President of the United States, from and where is the South Carolina National Bank of Charleston located?'}) (input_keys=None), Example({'question': 'The Earth Tower is in the casino that holds the studio of what station?', 'answer': 'WMOS'}) (input_keys={'question'}), Example({'question': 'What type of territory does Northern New Hampshire Correctional Facility and New Hampshire Department of Corrections have in common?', 'answer': 'state'}) (input_keys={'question'})]

'generate_answer.predict' predictor demos: [Example({'augmented': True, 'context': ['Thomas Keneally | Thomas Michael Keneally, AO (born 7 October 1935) is a prolific Australian novelist, playwright, and essayist. He is best known for writing "Schindler\'s Ark", the Booker Prize-winning novel of 1982 which was inspired by the efforts of Poldek Pfefferberg, a Holocaust survivor. The book would later be adapted to Steven Spielberg\'s "Schindler\'s List", which won the Academy Award for Best Picture.', 'Peter Straub | Peter Francis Straub (born March 2, 1943) is an American novelist and poet. His horror fiction has received numerous literary honors such as the Bram Stoker Award, World Fantasy Award, and International Horror Guild Award.', 'Thomas Martin Kennerly | Thomas Martin Kennerly (January 24, 1874 – July 29, 1962) was a United States federal judge. He was a Republican.', 'Poldek Pfefferberg | Leopold "Poldek" Pfefferberg (March 20, 1913 – March 9, 2001), also known as Leopold Page, was a Polish-American Holocaust survivor who inspired the Australian writer Thomas Keneally to write the Booker prize-winning novel "Schindler\'s Ark", which in turn was the basis for Steven Spielberg\'s film "Schindler\'s List".'], 'question': 'Are Thomas Keneally and Peter Straub both novelists?', 'reasoning': 'Thomas Keneally is described as an Australian novelist, playwright, and essayist. Peter Straub, on the other hand, is known as an American novelist and poet. Thus, both Thomas Keneally and Peter Straub are indeed both novelists.', 'answer': 'Yes'}) (input_keys=None), Example({'augmented': True, 'context': ['South Carolina National Bank of Charleston | One of the most important buildings on South Carolina’s oldest commercial street, the South Carolina National Bank building was built in 1817 as the Office of Discount and Deposit of the Second Bank of the United States. The bank was the only bank equipped to provide international banking services, which enabled the transfer of South Carolina rice and cotton to European markets. President Andrew Jackson later withdrew all government deposits, thereby destroying the bank. In 1836, when the Office of Discount and Deposit was liquidated, the Bank of Charleston purchased the building.', "Farmers' and Exchange Bank | The Farmers' and Exchange Bank is a historic commercial building at 141 East Bay Street in Charleston, South Carolina. Built in 1853–54, it is an architecturally distinctive building, with Moorish Revival features rarely seen in the United States. The building is recognizable for its use of muqarnas—characteristic of Persian and North African architecture—as well as its large arched windows and striking red sandstone facade. It was declared a National Historic Landmark in 1973.", 'First Citizens Bank of South Carolina | First Citizens Bank of South Carolina is a subsidiary of First Citizens BancShares, Inc., of Raleigh, North Carolina; it is the largest bank in the United States controlled by a single family. Prior to its acquisition by First Citizens BancShares Inc. of Raleigh, First Citizens Bancorporation, Inc. was a bank holding company based in Columbia, South Carolina with over $8 billion in assets. First Citizens Bank of South Carolina had branches in both South Carolina and Georgia. It was the second-largest commercial bank headquartered in South Carolina.', 'Fort Jackson (South Carolina) | Fort Jackson is a United States Army installation, which TRADOC operates on for Basic Combat Training (BCT), and is located next to Columbia, South Carolina. This installation is named for Andrew Jackson, a United States Army General and seventh President of the United States of America (1829–1837) who was born in the border region of North and South Carolina.', 'Andrew Jackson (disambiguation) | Andrew Jackson (1767–1845) was the 7th President of the United States.'], 'question': 'What country does South Carolina National Bank of Charleston and Andrew Jackson have in common?', 'reasoning': 'The South Carolina National Bank of Charleston was built for the Second Bank of the United States, which was an institution based in the United States. Andrew Jackson, the 7th President of the United States, also operated in the United States during the 19th century. Both institutions and the president were active in the U.S. during the same historical period, specifically related to American financial and political history in the early 19th century.', 'answer': 'United States'}) (input_keys=None), Example({'question': 'What type of territory does Northern New Hampshire Correctional Facility and New Hampshire Department of Corrections have in common?', 'answer': 'state'}) (input_keys={'question'}), Example({'question': 'The Earth Tower is in the casino that holds the studio of what station?', 'answer': 'WMOS'}) (input_keys={'question'})]

